The '''Panzerhaubitze 2000''' ({{IPA|de|ˈpant͡sɐhaʊ̯ˌbɪt͡sə t͡svaɪ̯ˈtaʊ̯zn̩t}}), meaning "armoured howitzer 2000"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kmweg.com/gb/frame.php?page=19 |title=Krauss-Maffei Wegmann – PZH 2000 – Ihr Partner rund um Wehrtechnik |website=Kmweg.com |access-date=20 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028115025/https://www.kmweg.com/gb/frame.php?page=19 |archive-date=28 October 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and abbreviated '''PzH 2000''', is a German [[155 mm]] [[Self-propelled gun|self-propelled howitzer]] developed by [[KNDS Deutschland]] (formerly Krauss-Maffei Wegmann (KMW)) and [[Rheinmetall]] in the 1980s and 1990s for the [[German Army]]. The PzH 2000 has automatic support for up to five rounds of [[Artillery#Multiple round simultaneous impact|multiple round simultaneous impact]]. Replenishment of shells is automated. Two operators can load 60 shells and propelling charges in less than 12&nbsp;minutes. The PzH 2000 equips the armies of [[German Army|Germany]], [[Italian Army|Italy]], [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Ukraine]], [[Royal Netherlands Army|Netherlands]], [[Hellenic Army|Greece]], [[Lithuanian Armed Forces|Lithuania]], [[Hungarian Defence Forces|Hungary]], [[Qatar Armed Forces|Qatar]], and [[Croatian Army|Croatia]], mostly replacing older systems such as the [[M109 howitzer]].

In November 2019, a PzH 2000 L52 gun fired a shell a distance of almost {{Convert|67|km|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/rheinmetall-sets-three-new-distance-records-for-indirect-fire-in-south-africa|title=Rheinmetall sets three new distance records for indirect fire in South Africa |website=edrmagazine.eu |date=27 November 2019 |access-date=4 May 2023}}</ref> Rheinmetall started testing a prototype L52 gun barrel with a new charge for a range of at least {{Convert|75|km|abbr=on}} since 2020.<ref name=janescw>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/rheinmetall-develops-new-long-range-howitzer|title=Rheinmetall develops new long-range howitzer|website=Janes.com|date=29 November 2019 |access-date=28 July 2022}}</ref> In May 2024, Rheinmetall announced that it would supply "a three-digit number" of L52 gun barrel systems for the Panzerhaubitze 2000 for "a European customer country".<ref>{{cite web |title=Press release - L52 gun barrel systems to European customer country |url=https://www.rheinmetall.com/en/media/news-watch/news/2024/05/2024-05-27-l52-gun-barrel-systems-to-european-customer-country |website=[[Rheinmetall]] |access-date=28 July 2024}}</ref>

== Development ==
In 1986, Italy, the United Kingdom and Germany agreed to terminate their existing development of the PzH 155-1 ([[SP70]]) programme, which had run into reliability problems and had design defects, notably being mounted on a modified tank chassis. German industry was asked for proposals to build a new design with a gun conforming to the JBMOU. Of the proposed designs, Wegmann's was selected.

== Design ==
[[File:De afsluiter van het kanon in een Duitse Panzerhaubitze 2000 (2138-012-008).jpg|thumb|left|The fighting compartment]]

[[Rheinmetall]] designed the 155&nbsp;mm 52-calibre JBMOU compliant rifled gun (60-rifles, right-hand spiral), which is [[chromium]]-lined over its entire 8 m length and includes a [[muzzle brake]] on the end. The gun uses a new modular charge system with six charges (five identical), which can be combined to provide the optimal total charge for the range to the target, as well as the conventional [[Shell (projectile)#Separate loading bagged charge|bagged charge]] systems. Primer is loaded separately via a conveyor belt, and the entire loading, laying and clearing are completely automated.

The maximum range of the gun with standard issue DM92 propellant charges is 30&nbsp;km with the standard DM121 boattail round, 40&nbsp;km with [[base bleed]] rounds, and 54&nbsp;km with M2005 V-LAP [[assisted projectile|rocket-assisted projectile]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=155mm Artillery Modular Charge System |url=https://www.rheinmetall.com/Rheinmetall%20Group/brochure-download/Weapon-Ammmunition/B284e0920-155mm-artillery-modular-charge-system.pdf}}</ref> With Rheinmetall's ERC (Extender Range Charge, previously known as the Top Charge) high pressure unitary charge, the range is 36&nbsp;km with DM121 BT round, 47&nbsp;km with M0121 BB round and 67&nbsp;km with the M2005 V-LAP RAP.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Extended Range Charge for 155mm artillery |date=27 November 2019 |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/rheinmetall-sets-three-new-distance-records-for-indirect-fire-in-south-africa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Valpolini |first=Paolo |date=2019-11-27 |title=Rheinmetall sets three new distance records for indirect fire in South Africa |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/rheinmetall-sets-three-new-distance-records-for-indirect-fire-in-south-africa |access-date=2023-11-28 |website=EDR Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref> The gun can also fire the [[SMArt 155]] artillery round used by Germany and Greece.

Wegmann supplied both the chassis, sharing some components with the [[Leopard 2]], and the turret for the gun. The system has superb cross-country performance because of its use of continuous tracks and considerable protection in the case of counter-fire. The turret includes a [[phased array]] [[radar]] on the front glacis for measuring the muzzle velocity of each round fired. Laying data can be automatically provided via encrypted radio from the battery fire direction centre.

A lighter, more air-portable version developed by KMW and called the [[Artillery Gun Module]] uses the gun in a module fitted to a lighter chassis.

In December 2013, [[Raytheon]] and the German Army completed compatibility testing for the [[M982 Excalibur]] extended range guided artillery shell with the PzH 2000. Ten Excaliburs were fired at ranges from 9 to 48&nbsp;km. Shells hit within 3 m of their targets, with an average miss distance of 1 m at 48&nbsp;km.<ref>[http://www.deagel.com/news/German-Army-PzH-2000-Howitzer-Test-Fires-Excalibur-155mm-Artillery-Projectile_n000012199.aspx German Army PzH 2000 Howitzer Test Fires Excalibur 155mm Artillery Projectile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810155806/http://www.deagel.com/news/German-Army-PzH-2000-Howitzer-Test-Fires-Excalibur-155mm-Artillery-Projectile_n000012199.aspx |date=10 August 2014 }} - Deagel.com, 10 December 2013</ref>

=== Upgrades ===

==== PzH 2000 A1 ====
Upgrades:<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Valpolini |first=Paolo |date=2025-10-29 |title=KNDS Deutschland, where does the PzH 2000 go? |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/knds-deutschland-where-does-the-pzh-2000-go |access-date=2025-11-25 |website=EDR Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref>

* Improved barrel laying system for a better accuracy.
* Navigation system more accurate.

==== PzH 2000 A2 ====
Upgrades:<ref>{{Cite web |title=Panzerhaubitze 2000 A2 |url=https://www.panzer-modell.de/referenz/in_detail/pzh2000a2/pzh2000.htm |access-date=2025-11-25 |website=www.panzer-modell.de}}</ref><ref name=":4" />

* Auxiliary power unit of 1.9 kW added on the PzH 2000.
* Ventilation opening at the rear of the turret added.
* Cooling system added for the charges.
* Stowage of the tow cable relocated.

==== PzH 2000 A3 ====
The PzH 2000 A3 focused on the anti-mine protection, but it never enter service, and the upgrades were not included in the A4 variant.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Valpolini |first=Paolo |date=2025-10-29 |title=KNDS Deutschland, where does the PzH 2000 go? |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/knds-deutschland-where-does-the-pzh-2000-go |access-date=2025-11-25 |website=EDR Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== PzH 2000 A4 ====
The first PzH 2000 in that variant was rolled out in November 2025. It is a newly produced gun, one that replaces the guns supplied to Ukraine for the German Army.<ref name=":5" />

The upgrades focus on the electronic aspect:<ref name=":5" />

* The architecture of the weapon system remains a mix of analogue and digital systems.
* KNDS Deutschland Centurion: a new fire control computer, replacing the MICMOS (1980s /1990s technology).
* A new fuse programming station installed.
* Improvement of the electronic architecture. 
* Integration of the Vulcano 155mm ammunition.

==== PzH 2000 A5 ====
In 2021, Germany and the Netherlands agreed to jointly define & execute a Mid-Life Update to the operational Pzh2000 in their inventories and ensure standardisation and availability.

The MLU variant is the PzH 2000 A5, it is designed for all customers, with core common elements, and optional elements, it is expected to be ready by 2028.<ref name=":5" />

Upgrades:<ref name=":5" />

* Transition to a fully electronic / digital architecture, with a semi-open architecture (standardised electronic interfaces) of the weapon system. 
* Ammunition auto loader improvements.
* Gun laying system improvements.
* Two-slip ring solution for the turret (to cope with the ammunition handling system).

==Combat record and alterations==
[[File:Panzerhaubitze 2000 - Bundeswehr Military History Museum, Dresden.jpg|thumb|Panzerhaubitze 2000 – Bundeswehr Military History Museum, Dresden]]{{See also|War in Afghanistan (2001–2021)}}
The PzH 2000 was used for the first time in combat by the [[Fire Support Command]] of the [[Royal Netherlands Army]] in August 2006 against [[Taliban]] targets in [[Kandahar Province]], [[Afghanistan]], in support of [[Operation Medusa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kmweg.com/gb/spezial.php?id%3D21 |title=Krauss-Maffei Wegmann – Ihr Partner rund um Wehrtechnik |access-date=2 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928100123/https://www.kmweg.com/gb/spezial.php?id=21 |archive-date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> It was then used regularly in support of coalition troops in [[Uruzgan Province|Uruzgan province]]. The PzH 2000 was also used extensively during the [[Battle of Chora]] in June 2007. It was known as "the long arm of [[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF]]" and proved to be accurate and effective. However, the gun was criticised by the Dutch in Uruzgan province as the [[NBC protection system|NBC system]], designed for use in Europe, could not cope with the high level of dust in Afghanistan.

The guns have been modified with additional armor being fitted to the roof to protect against mortar rounds. There have been reports of other problems, including the need to keep it in the shade unless actually firing, the damage done when traveling on poorly built roads, and a significant 'cold gun' effect{{Clarify|date=August 2022}} necessitating the use of 'warmers'.

Starting in June 2010 as a result of the [[Good Friday Battle]], German ISAF troops at PRT [[Kunduz]] had three PzH 2000s at their disposal. They were first used on 10 July 2010 to provide support for the recovery of a damaged vehicle. This was the first time in its history that the [[Bundeswehr]] has used heavy artillery in combat.<ref>[http://www.abendblatt.de/politik/ausland/article1564057/Bundeswehr-setzt-erstmals-schwere-Artillerie-ein.html Bundeswehr setzt erstmals schwere Artillerie ein] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205135045/http://www.abendblatt.de/politik/ausland/article1564057/Bundeswehr-setzt-erstmals-schwere-Artillerie-ein.html |date=5 December 2013 }}. Hamburger Abendblatt, 12 July 2010</ref> The PzH 2000 also played a key role during [[Operation Halmazag]] in November 2010, when the villages of Isa Khel and Quatliam were retaken from the Taliban by German paratroopers.<ref>[http://www.derwesten-recherche.org/2012/11/der-kampf-um-quatliam/ Der Kampf um Quatliam] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204070922/http://www.derwesten-recherche.org/2012/11/der-kampf-um-quatliam/ |date=4 December 2013 }}, by [[David Schraven]] {{in lang|de}}</ref>

=== Russian invasion of Ukraine ===
On 21 June 2022, twelve PzH 2000s were deployed to Ukraine; seven came from Germany and five from the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 June 2022 |title=First heavy weapons from Germany arrive in Ukraine| url=https://www.dw.com/en/first-heavy-weapons-from-germany-arrive-in-ukraine/a-62211051 |access-date=22 June 2022 |website=www.dw.com |language=en}}</ref> After a couple of weeks of intensive use, the guns required repairs, and error messages were being displayed as they are designed and built to fire no more than 100 shots a day.<ref name=faz2022>[https://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/ukraine-krieg-panzerhaubitzen-muessen-schon-repariert-werden-18208150.html?GEPC=s6 Gelieferte Panzerhaubitzen müssen schon repariert werden], FAZ, 29 July 2022.</ref> Germany considers 100 shots per day "a high-intensity mission". Ukraine has consistently exceeded this number, placing stress on the loading mechanism. Ukraine also fired "special ammunition at too great a distance." The Bundeswehr sent spare parts and a repair facility in [[Lithuania]] was chosen to repair the weapons.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 October 2022|title= Lithuania Has Repaired PzH 2000 Howitzer and Returning Them to Service of Ukraine's Armed Forces|author1=| url= https://en.defence-ua.com/industries/lithuania_has_repaired_pzh_2000_howitzer_and_returning_them_to_service_of_ukraines_armed_forces-4531.html |access-date=2 December 2022 |website= defence-ua.com| language=en}}</ref> This came as Ukraine and KMW entered into a 1.7 billion euro deal to purchase 100 PzH 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 July 2022|title= German PzH 2000s in Ukraine wear out: error message after heavy fire | author1= Boyko Nikolov | url= https://bulgarianmilitary.com/amp/2022/07/30/german-pzh-2000s-in-ukraine-wear-out-error-message-after-heavy-fire/ |access-date=2 August 2022 |website= bulgarianmilitary.com |language=en}}</ref>

Russian state news agency [[TASS]] reported that a PzH 2000 was destroyed by Russian forces in [[Kherson Oblast]] on 30 October 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Russian forces wipe out German PzH 2000 artillery system in Ukraine operation |url=https://tass.com/politics/1530253 |access-date=31 October 2022 |website=TASS}}</ref> 

The open-source intelligence site [[Oryx (website)|Oryx]] reported one visually confirmed destroyed and one damaged Ukrainian PzH 2000 based on publicly available footage.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Oryx |title=Attack On Europe: Documenting Ukrainian Equipment Losses During The 2022 Russian Invasion Of Ukraine |url=https://www.oryxspioenkop.com/2022/02/attack-on-europe-documenting-ukrainian.html |access-date=2023-01-12|website=Oryx}}</ref>

Due to the intensity of artillery fire on the battlefield, Lithuania undertook to repair twelve of the howitzers,<ref>[https://mil.in.ua/en/news/lithuania-to-repair-12-pzh-2000-howitzers-for-ukraine/ Lithuania to repair 12 PzH 2000 howitzers for Ukraine]</ref> finishing repair work on six by December 2022. By this time, the number of PzH 2000s sent to Ukraine rose to twenty-two; fourteen from Germany and eight from the Netherlands.<ref>[https://mil.in.ua/en/news/lithuania-hands-over-two-more-repaired-pzh-2000-and-ammunition-to-ukraine/ Lithuania hands over two more repaired PzH 2000 and ammunition to Ukraine]</ref> As of February 2023, fifteen of the howitzers were waiting to be repaired in [[Slovakia]], but were being held up at the border for several weeks due to legal issues.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.de/politik/deutschland/ukraine-krieg-slowakei-blockiert-reparatur-deutscher-waffen/ An der Grenze stauen sich kaputte Panzerhaubitzen: Slowakei blockiert Reparatur deutscher Waffen für den Ukraine-Krieg]</ref><ref>[https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2023/02/16/7389678/ Slovakia is not allowing German howitzers to cross border from Ukraine for repairs for several weeks]</ref>

According to the Rheinmetall CEO Armin Papperger the barrels of the PzH 2000 had an expected lifetime of around 4,500 shots, but to the surprise of the manufacturer they have achieved up to 20,000 in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web |author=n-tv NACHRICHTEN |url=https://www.n-tv.de/wirtschaft/Rheinmetall-Chef-raeumt-Verluste-deutscher-Waffen-in-Ukraine-ein-article24181343.html |title=Rheinmetall-Chef räumt Verluste deutscher Waffen in Ukraine ein |language=de |access-date=2023-06-11}}</ref>

== Production status ==
As of June 2024, 41 remain to be manufactured, it includes 1 for Hungary, 22 for Germany and 18 for Ukraine.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=18 June 2024 |title=KNDS OFFERS THE COMPLETE RANGE OF PROVEN ARTILLERY SYSTEMS |url=https://www.knds.fr/en/our-news/latest-news/knds-offers-complete-range-proven-artillery-systems}}</ref>

