: 24 ordered in 2013,<ref>{{cite press release |title=Krauss-Maffei Wegmann Supports Qatar's Army Moderni zation |date=18 April 2013 |publisher=Krauss-Maffei Wegmann GmbH & Co. KG |url=http://www.kmweg.de/de/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Press_Releases/Press_Release_Army_modernization_Qatar.pdf |access-date=18 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531091044/http://www.kmweg.de/de/fileadmin/user_upload/pdfs/Press_Releases/Press_Release_Army_modernization_Qatar.pdf |archive-date=31 May 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> first three delivered in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hickmann |first1=Christoph |last2=Berlin |first2=Georg Mascolo |date=22 October 2015 |title=Waffenexporte: Deutschland liefert Kampfpanzer nach Katar |url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/waffenexporte-deutschland-liefert-kampfpanzer-nach-katar-1.2703573 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102032945/http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/waffenexporte-deutschland-liefert-kampfpanzer-nach-katar-1.2703573 |archive-date=2 January 2017 |access-date=28 December 2016 |via=Sueddeutsche.de}}</ref> In September 2024 12 were returned to Germany to be provided to Ukraine in a ''Ringtausch'' arrangement in exchange for replacement with 12 [[RCH 155|RCH-155]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stritzel |first1=Björn |date=15 September 2024 |title=Waffen für Katar, aber nicht für Israel? |url=https://www.bild.de/politik/ausland-und-internationales/ruestungsdeals-der-regierung-waffen-fuer-katar-aber-nicht-fuer-israel-66e45994cb180e1cf920787c |via=Bild.de}}</ref>
; {{flag|Ukraine}} (38)
: 28 delivered.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Cannoni e mezzi hi tech, ecco le armi date dall'Italia per l'offensiva ucraina |url=https://www.repubblica.it/esteri/2022/10/29/news/ucraina_kiev_armi_italia-372176795/ |access-date=30 October 2022 |website=la Repubblica |language=it}}</ref> During the [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]], it was announced on 20 April 2022 that five Dutch PzH 2000s would be transferred to Ukraine, with ammunition and training to be provided by Germany.<ref>{{cite news |date=20 April 2022 |title=Deutschland bildet offenbar Ukrainer an Panzerhaubitze 2000 aus |url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/deutschland/ukraine-krieg-deutschland-bildet-offenbar-ukrainer-an-panzerhaubitze-2000-aus/28264476.html |access-date=20 April 2022 |work=Handelsblatt |language=German}}</ref> On 6 May, it was announced that Ukraine would receive seven units from German army stocks which were undergoing maintenance.<ref>{{cite news |date=6 May 2022 |title=Deutschland liefert Panzerhaubitzen |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/ukraine-lambrecht-panzerhaubitzen-101.html |access-date=2 July 2022 |work=Tagesschau |language=German}}</ref> On 7 May, Chancellor [[Olaf Scholz]] agreed to supply the ammunition required, straight from industry to Ukrainian forces, without having to go through the German government for approval in the future.<ref name="reut7">{{cite news |date=7 May 2022 |title=Germany to send seven howitzers to Ukraine in further policy reversal |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/germany-send-seven-self-propelled-howitzers-ukraine-2022-05-06/ |access-date=7 May 2022 |work=Reuters |language=English}}</ref> Training of Ukrainian artillery crews started on 11 May 2022 at the Bundeswehr's artillery school in [[Idar-Oberstein]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 May 2022 |title=Ukrainische Soldaten zur Ausbildung in Rheinland-Pfalz angekommen |url=https://www.swr.de/swraktuell/rheinland-pfalz/trier/soldaten-ukraine-ausbildung-100.html |access-date=2 July 2022 |work=SWR Aktuell |language=German |archive-date=1 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220701231253/https://www.swr.de/swraktuell/rheinland-pfalz/trier/soldaten-ukraine-ausbildung-100.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 21 June, Ukrainian [[Minister of Defence of Ukraine|Minister of Defence]] [[Oleksii Reznikov]] announced that the first PzH 2000s had entered Ukrainian service.<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1539225560588734466 |user=oleksiireznikov |title=Panzerhaubitze 2000 are finally part of 155 mm howitzer arsenal of the Ukrainian artillery |first=Oleksii |last=Reznikov |author-link=Oleksii Reznikov |date=21 June 2022 |access-date=26 December 2022 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221208005725/https://twitter.com/oleksiireznikov/status/1539225560588734466 |archive-date=8 December 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' reported on 27 July that Germany had agreed to sell 100 more PzH 2000s to Ukraine.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last1=Gebauer |first1=Matthias |last2=Traufetter |first2=Gerald |date=28 July 2022 |title=(S+) Ukraine-Krieg: Berlin genehmigt Verkauf von 100 Panzerhaubitzen |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/ukraine-darf-100-panzerhaubitzen-kaufen-a-6e1c331d-0da2-4218-9653-2ee96560da9d |access-date=28 July 2022 |website=Spiegel.de}}</ref> By this time, many PzH 2000 ammo loading mechanisms had broken down due to considerable strain: while the PzH 2000 is designed to fire 100 shells per day, the Ukrainians likely fired the gun much more often. In addition to shipping necessary spare parts to Ukraine, the German government was negotiating the creation of a repair center for its equipment in Poland.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Front News - Ukraine appealed to Germany because of problems with PzH 2000 howitzers |url=https://frontnews.eu/en/news/details/37325}}</ref> In October 2022, the howitzers were sent to Lithuania because Poland denied the German request for exclusive access to the [[Huta Stalowa Wola]] facilities, as it would halt all production in the factory (HSW manufactures and services [[AHS Krab|Krab]] SPGs for Poland and Ukraine, among other weapon systems).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Behrendt |first=Paweł |date=2022-10-08 |title=Remonty ukraińskich PzH 2000 w Polsce – co i jak? |url=https://www.konflikty.pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/remonty-pzh-2000-w-polsce/ |access-date=2023-01-13 |website=Konflikty.pl |language=pl-PL}}</ref> Eventually, a planned repair center in Slovakia will shorten the route to and from the war zone in Ukraine. In late 2023, it emerged that Ukraine did not sign the purchase agreement for the delivery of 100 PzH 2000.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ukraine and Germany fail to seal deal for 100 PzH 2000 self-propelled howitzers |url=https://newsukraine.rbc.ua/news/ukraine-and-germany-fail-to-seal-deal-for-1700057548.html |access-date=2024-01-18 |website=RBC-Ukraine |language=en}}</ref>
: In February 2024, Germany announced supporting Ukraine with 18 additional PzH 2000 and 18 more [[RCH 155|RCH-155]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-02-16 |title=Military support for Ukraine {{!}} Federal Government |url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-en/search/military-support-ukraine-2054992 |access-date=2024-02-18 |website=Website of the Federal Government {{!}} Bundesregierung |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=ES&T Redaktion |date=2024-02-18 |title=Deutschland unterstützt die Ukraine weiter mit einer Sicherheitsvereinbarung und dem "Münchner Paket" |url=https://esut.de/2024/02/meldungen/47608/deutschland-unterstuetzt-die-ukraine-weiter-mit-einer-sicherheitsvereinbarung-und-dem-muenchner-paket/ |access-date=2024-02-18 |website=esut.de |language=de-DE}}</ref>

=== Potential sales ===

;{{flag|Germany}} (54)
: 54 additional systems are in discussion as of June 2024, to be supplied to Germany and to Ukraine.<ref name=":2" />

=== Failed bids ===

;{{flag|Australia}}
: The PzH 2000 was a contender for Phase 1C of Australia's Land 17 Artillery Replacement Programme, until that phase of the project was cancelled in May 2012.<ref>{{cite news |date=3 May 2012 |title=Rethink of Defence projects to save billions |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503202448/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042 |archive-date=3 May 2012 |access-date=3 May 2012 |publisher=[[ABC Online]]}}</ref>
;{{flag|Finland}} 
: Finland tested a PzH 2000 alongside the [[155mm SpGH ZUZANA]] and [[AS-90]] "Braveheart". Tests ended in 1998; more of the cheaper [[155 GH 52 APU|155 K 98]] field guns were bought instead of self-propelled systems.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eversti J.A.Alasjärvi - Suomen Tykistömuseo |url=http://www.tykistomuseo.fi/historia/tykiston_tarkastajat/alasjarvi/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514123854/http://www.tykistomuseo.fi/historia/tykiston_tarkastajat/alasjarvi/ |archive-date=14 May 2011 |access-date=4 March 2011}}</ref>
;{{flag|Germany}} - Navy
: The [[German Navy]] evaluated a modified system known as [[MONARC]] for installation onboard [[frigate]]s; while the system performed well, components were difficult to protect against corrosion. Sweden evaluated a slightly modified version, but selected the [[Archer Artillery System]] instead.
;{{flag|Romania}} (54)
: The PzH 2000 participated in the Romanian tracked self-propelled artillery system competition against the Korean [[K9 Thunder]] and the Turkish [[T-155 Fırtına|T-155 Fırtına II]] which included 54 howitzers in total.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Romania Short-lists German, Turkish & S.Korean howitzers |url=https://www.defensemirror.com/news/35081/Romania_Short_lists_German__Turkish___S_Korean_howitzers |access-date=2024-01-26 |website=www.defensemirror.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Adamowski |first=Jaroslaw |date=2024-01-22 |title=Romanian government readies fighting vehicle, howitzer deals in 2024 |url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2024/01/22/romanian-government-readies-fighting-vehicle-howitzer-deals-in-2024/ |access-date=2024-01-26 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> The Korean offer was the only one to progress in the contract bid, and negotiations between South Korea and Romania were finished in April 2024,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://monitorulapararii.ro/sud-coreenii-de-la-hanwha-au-pus-ochii-pe-romania-vor-deschiderea-unui-centru-de-logistica-si-mentenanta-pentru-obuzierele-autopropulsate-k9-dar-1-54656|title=Sud coreenii de la Hanwha au pus ochii pe România. Vor deschiderea unui centru de logistică şi mentenanţă pentru obuzierele autopropulsate K9, dar planurile sunt mult mai mari. Partea I|language=ro|author=Andreea Soare|website=monitorulapararii.ro|date=26 April 2024}}</ref> with the contract signed in June 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvrinfo.ro/armata-romana-cumpara-cateva-zeci-de-obuziere-senilate-k-9-tunet-din-coreea-de-sud/|title=Armata română cumpără câteva zeci de obuziere șenilate K-9 Tunet, din Coreea de Sud|language=ro|website=tvrinfo.ro|date=19 June 2024}}</ref>
;{{flag|Turkey}}
: In 1999, despite showing interest in K9 Thunder, there was no business deals made as Turkey was planning to produce German Panzerhaubitze 2000 at that time. Another meeting was held on 4 October, regarding K9 production in Turkey and solution for import restriction on MTU Friedrichshafen engines by German government. As Turkey's plan to build PzH2000 eventually became halted by Germany, South Korea and Turkey signed MOU for [[T-155 Fırtına]].<ref name="Turkey Sales">{{cite news |url=https://www.haebyeong.com/mnddata/12348 |script-title=ko:[첨단무기 개발비화]세계 최강의 K-9 자주포(VIII) 신인호 국방일보 |publisher=Republic of Korea Marine Corps |date=2010-06-28 |language=Korean |newspaper=해병닷컴 }}</ref>
;{{flag|United States}}
: The PzH 2000 was considered for the [[United States Army|US Army]]'s [[XM2001 Crusader|Crusader]] concept system, but several requirements of the Crusader made it unsuitable. The Crusader specifications placed the crew and gun in separate compartments, allowing a single highly armoured crew compartment to control the firing of an entire battery of guns through intervehicle links. In addition, the Crusader included an automated ammunition tender, and an active cooled barrel.<ref>{{Cite web |title=General Accounting Office |url=https://fas.org/man/gao/nsiad-97-121.htm |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409032325/https://fas.org/man/gao/nsiad-97-121.htm |archive-date=9 April 2015 |access-date=4 April 2015}}</ref>

==RCH 155 vs Panzerhaubitze 2000==
The [[RCH 155]] (Remote Controlled Howitzer 155&nbsp;mm) is a wheeled [[self-propelled howitzer]] developed by [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann]] (now [[KNDS Deutschland]]), a German defence company.

The RCH 155 Module takes the firepower and the [[External ballistics|range]] of the Panzerhaubitze 2000 by using its gun ([[155 mm calibre|155 mm L/52]]), and combines it with an automated and remotely controlled gun module. 
It is the world's first howitzer that can fire while in motion (like i.e. the [[Leopard 2]]).<ref>{{cite web |last=Hoffmann |first=Lars |date=20 August 2021 |title=Radhaubitze RCH 155 – KMW shows firing on the move for the first time |url=https://esut.de/2021/08/fachbeitraege/ruestung/29196/rch-155-kmw-zeigt-schuss-aus-der-bewegung/}}</ref>
This is mainly to avoid enemy counter-artillery fire, as modern [[counter-battery radar]]s (as [[COBRA (radar)|COBRA]]) can reconnoitre fire positions after firing in near real-time.

The crew of the RCH 155 consists of only two people: a commander and a military driver. 
The Panzerhaubitze 2000 has five: commander, driver, gunner, and two loaders.

